"Yoneyama S., Tanaka N.","Smart film actuators using biomass plastic",2011,"Smart Materials and Structures","20","4", 045012,"","",,,10.1088/0964-1726/20/4/045012,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79953246066&partnerID=40&md5=734c60ebc891546d87ced3f0ca5c447a","Department of Aerospace Engineering, Tokyo Metropolitan University, 6-6 Asahigaoka, Hino-city, 191-0065, Tokyo, Japan","Yoneyama, S., Department of Aerospace Engineering, Tokyo Metropolitan University, 6-6 Asahigaoka, Hino-city, 191-0065, Tokyo, Japan; Tanaka, N., Department of Aerospace Engineering, Tokyo Metropolitan University, 6-6 Asahigaoka, Hino-city, 191-0065, Tokyo, Japan","This paper presents a novel smart film actuator based on the use of a biomass plastic as a piezoelectric film. Conventional polymeric smart sensors and actuators have been based upon synthetic piezoelectric polymer films such as PVDF. Almost all synthetic polymers are made from nearly depleted oil resources. In addition combustion of their materials releases carbon dioxide, thereby contributing to global warming. Thus at least two important sustainability principles are violated when employing synthetic polymers: avoiding depletable resources and avoiding ecosystem destruction. To overcome such problems, industrial plastic products made from synthetic polymers were developed to replace oil-based plastics with biomass plastics. This paper applies a biomass plastic with piezoelectricity such as poly-L-lactic acid (PLLA). Asa result, PLLA film becomes a distributed parameter actuator perse, hence an environmentally conscious smart film actuator is developed. Firstly, this paper overviews the fundamental properties of piezoelectric synthetic polymers and biopolymers. The concept of carbon neutrality using biopolymers is mentioned. Then a two-dimensional modal actuator for exciting a specific structural mode is proposed. Furthermore, a biomass plastic-based cantilever beam with the capability of modal actuation is developed, the validity of the proposed smart film actuator based upon a biomass plastic being analytically as well as experimentally verified. © 2011 IOP Publishing Ltd.",,"Distributed parameter; Fundamental properties; Modal actuators; Oil resource; Piezoelectric film; Piezoelectric polymer film; PLLA; Poly L lactic acid; Sensors and actuators; Structural modes; Sustainability principles; Synthetic polymers; Biomass; Biomolecules; Biopolymers; Carbon dioxide; Crystallography; Elastomers; Global warming; Lactic acid; Organic polymers; Petroleum deposits; Piezoelectric actuators; Piezoelectricity; Plastic products; Polymer films; Polymeric films; Polymers",,,,,,"Furukawa, T., Piezoelectricity and pyroelectricity in vinilidene fluoride/ trifluoroethylene copolymers (1986) J. Appl. Phys., 25 (PART 1), pp. 1178-1182. , NO. 8; Fukada, E., History and recent progress in piezoelectric polymers (2000) IEEE Trans. Ultrason., 47 (6), pp. 1277-1290; Yagi Toshiharu, Tatemoto Masayoshi, Sako Jun-ichi, Transition behavior and dielectric properties in trifluoroethylene and vinylidene fluoride copolymers (1980) Polymer Journal, 12 (4), pp. 209-223; Tajitsu, Y., Crystalline phase transition in the copolymer of vinylidene fluoride and trifluoroethylen (1980) Appl. Phys. Lett., 36 (4), pp. 286-288; Kawai, H., The piezoelectricity of poly (vinylidene fluoride) (1969) Japan. J. Appl. Phys., 8 (7), pp. 975-976. , vinylidene fluoride; Fukada, E., New piezoelectric polymers (1998) Japan. J. Appl. Phys., 37 (PART 1), pp. 2775-2780. , NO. 5B; Fukada, E., Piezoelectricity of wood (1955) J. Phys. Soc. Japan, 10 (2), pp. 149-154; Ueda Hiroyoshi, Fukada Eiichi, Piezoelectric relaxations in collagen gelatin systems (1979) Polym J, 11 (2), pp. 103-111; Fukada, E., Piezoelectric properties of poly-L-lactic acid (1991) Rep. Prog. Polym. Phys. Japan, 34, pp. 269-272; Furukawa, T., Fukada, E., Piezoelectric effect and its temperature variation in optically active polypropylene-oxide (1969) Nature, 221 (5187), pp. 1235-1236; Ando Yutaka, Fukada Eiichi, Piezoelectric properties and molecular motion of poly-β- hydroxybutyrate films (1984) Journal of polymer science. Part A-2, Polymer physics, 22 (10), pp. 1821-1834; Imoto, K., Piezoelectric motion of poly (L-lactic acid) film improved by supercritical CO 2 treatment (2009) Japan. J. Appl. Phys., 48; Nakiri, T., Piezoelectric characteristics of polymer film oriented under a strong magnetic field (2004) Japan. J. Appl. Phys., 43 (9 B), pp. 6769-6774; Tajitsu, Y., Piezoelectric poly-L-lactic acid film prepared by a new method (2003) Japan. J. Appl. Phys., 42 (PART 1), pp. 6172-6175. , NO. 9B; Honda, M., Electrically controlled piezoelectric motion of piezoelectric chiral polymeric fibers (2008) Japan. J. Appl. Phys., 47 (9), pp. 7642-7645; Honda, M., Hayashi, K., Morii, K., Kawai, S., Morimoto, Y., Tajitsu, Y., Piezoelectricity of chiral polymeric fibers (2007) Japanese Journal of Applied Physics, Part 1: Regular Papers and Short Notes and Review Papers, 46 (10 B), pp. 7122-7124. , http://jjap.ipap.jp/link?JJAP/46/7122/pdf, DOI 10.1143/JJAP.46.7122; Terentjev, E.M., Warner, M., Piezoelectricity of chiral nematic elastomers (1999) European Physical Journal B, 8 (4), pp. 595-601; Maeda, H., The dependence on temperature and hydration of piezoelectric, dielectric and elastic constants of bone (1976) Japan. J. Appl. Phys., 15 (12), pp. 2333-2336; Fukada, E., Piezoelectricity in polymers and biological materials (1968) Ultrasonics, 6 (4), pp. 229-234; Furukawa, T., Fukada, E., Piezoelectric relaxation in composite epoxy-PZT system due to ionic conduction (1977) Japan. J. Appl. Phys., 16 (3), pp. 453-458; Miller, S.A., Landis, A.E., Theis, T.L., Environmental trade-offs of biobased production (2007) Environmental Science and Technology, 41 (15), pp. 5176-5182; Brian, W.M., Global environmental chemistry (1992) The Science of Global Change, 483, pp. 5-20. , Washington: ACS; Jian, F.Z., Xiuzhi, S., Mechanical properties of poly (